# Searching Algorithms

# Introduction

Searching algorithms are used to find a specific element in a collection of data such as arrays, lists, or databases.
They are one of the most important topics in Data Structures and Algorithms because searching operations are used in:

* Databases
* Search engines
* Applications
* Operating systems
* Artificial Intelligence systems

The efficiency of a searching algorithm is measured using:

* Time Complexity
* Space Complexity

---

# Types of Searching Algorithms

Searching algorithms are mainly divided into:

1. Sequential Searching
2. Interval-Based Searching

---

# 1. Linear Search

# Introduction

Linear Search is the simplest searching algorithm.
It checks each element one by one until the target element is found or the list ends.

It is also called:

* Sequential Search

---

# Working Principle

The algorithm:

1. Starts from the first element
2. Compares each element with the target
3. Stops if match is found
4. Continues until end of array

---

# Algorithm Steps

1. Start from index 0
2. Compare current element with target
3. If equal → return index
4. Else move to next element
5. Repeat until element found or array ends

---

# Example

## Array

```text id="s1"
10 20 30 40 50
```

## Target

```text id="s2"
40
```

---

# Searching Process

| Step | Element Checked | Result    |
| ---- | --------------- | --------- |
| 1    | 10              | Not Found |
| 2    | 20              | Not Found |
| 3    | 30              | Not Found |
| 4    | 40              | Found     |

---

# Pseudocode

```text id="s3"
for each element in array
    if element == target
        return index
return not found
```

---

# JavaScript Example

```javascript id="s4"
function linearSearch(arr, target) {
    for(let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
        if(arr[i] === target) {
            return i;
        }
    }
    return -1;
}

console.log(linearSearch([10,20,30,40], 30));
```

---

# Time Complexity

| Case         | Complexity |
| ------------ | ---------- |
| Best Case    | O(1)       |
| Average Case | O(n)       |
| Worst Case   | O(n)       |

---

# Space Complexity

```text id="s5"
O(1)
```

---

# Advantages

* Simple to implement
* Works on unsorted data
* No preprocessing required

---

# Disadvantages

* Slow for large datasets
* Inefficient compared to advanced searches

---

# Applications

* Small datasets
* Unsorted arrays
* Simple search operations

---

# 2. Binary Search

# Introduction

Binary Search is an efficient searching algorithm that works only on sorted arrays.

It divides the search space into two halves repeatedly.

---

# Working Principle

1. Find middle element
2. Compare target with middle
3. If target smaller → search left half
4. If target larger → search right half
5. Repeat until found

---

# Requirement

# Array must be sorted

---

# Example

## Array

```text id="s6"
10 20 30 40 50 60 70
```

## Target

```text id="s7"
50
```

---

# Searching Process

| Step | Middle Element | Result       |
| ---- | -------------- | ------------ |
| 1    | 40             | Search Right |
| 2    | 60             | Search Left  |
| 3    | 50             | Found        |

---

# Formula

mid = \frac{low + high}{2}

---

# JavaScript Example

```javascript id="s8"
function binarySearch(arr, target) {

    let low = 0;
    let high = arr.length - 1;

    while(low <= high) {

        let mid = Math.floor((low + high) / 2);

        if(arr[mid] === target) {
            return mid;
        }

        else if(arr[mid] < target) {
            low = mid + 1;
        }

        else {
            high = mid - 1;
        }
    }

    return -1;
}
```

---

# Time Complexity

| Case         | Complexity |
| ------------ | ---------- |
| Best Case    | O(1)       |
| Average Case | O(log n)   |
| Worst Case   | O(log n)   |

---

# Space Complexity

```text id="s9"
O(1)
```

---

# Advantages

* Very fast
* Efficient for large datasets
* Fewer comparisons

---

# Disadvantages

* Requires sorted data
* Sorting may take extra time

---

# Applications

* Dictionary searching
* Database indexing
* Searching in large systems

---

# 3. Jump Search

# Introduction

Jump Search searches elements by jumping fixed steps instead of checking every element.

It works on:

# Sorted Arrays

---

# Working Principle

1. Jump ahead by block size
2. Find block containing target
3. Perform linear search inside block

---

# Optimal Jump Size

Jump\ Size = \sqrt{n}

---

# Example

## Array

```text id="s10"
10 20 30 40 50 60 70 80 90
```

## Jump Size

```text id="s11"
3
```

---

# Process

* Jump from 10 → 40 → 70
* Target found between 40 and 70
* Apply linear search

---

# JavaScript Example

```javascript id="s12"
function jumpSearch(arr, target) {

    let n = arr.length;
    let step = Math.floor(Math.sqrt(n));
    let prev = 0;

    while(arr[Math.min(step, n)-1] < target) {
        prev = step;
        step += Math.floor(Math.sqrt(n));

        if(prev >= n)
            return -1;
    }

    while(arr[prev] < target) {
        prev++;

        if(prev == Math.min(step, n))
            return -1;
    }

    if(arr[prev] == target)
        return prev;

    return -1;
}
```

---

# Time Complexity

| Case         | Complexity |
| ------------ | ---------- |
| Best Case    | O(1)       |
| Average Case | O(√n)      |
| Worst Case   | O(√n)      |

---

# Advantages

* Faster than linear search
* Easy implementation

---

# Disadvantages

* Requires sorted array
* Slower than binary search

---

# Applications

* Medium-sized sorted datasets

---

# 4. Interpolation Search

# Introduction

Interpolation Search improves Binary Search for uniformly distributed data.

It estimates probable position of target.

---

# Working Principle

Instead of middle position, estimated position is calculated.

---

# Formula

pos = low + \frac{(target - arr[low])(high - low)}{arr[high] - arr[low]}

---

# Example

## Array

```text id="s13"
10 20 30 40 50 60 70
```

## Target

```text id="s14"
60
```

Interpolation predicts near actual position.

---

# Time Complexity

| Case         | Complexity   |
| ------------ | ------------ |
| Best Case    | O(1)         |
| Average Case | O(log log n) |
| Worst Case   | O(n)         |

---

# Advantages

* Faster for uniformly distributed data

---

# Disadvantages

* Poor performance for uneven data

---

# Applications

* Telephone directories
* Large sorted databases

---

# 5. Exponential Search

# Introduction

Exponential Search is useful for very large or infinite-sized arrays.

It combines:

* Binary Search
* Exponential jumps

---

# Working Principle

1. Find range exponentially
2. Apply binary search inside range

---

# Example

## Array

```text id="s15"
2 4 8 16 32 64 128
```

## Target

```text id="s16"
64
```

Steps:

* Check 1,2,4...
* Find suitable range
* Apply binary search

---

# JavaScript Example

```javascript id="s17"
function exponentialSearch(arr, target) {

    if(arr[0] == target)
        return 0;

    let i = 1;

    while(i < arr.length && arr[i] <= target) {
        i = i * 2;
    }

    return binarySearch(arr, target);
}
```

---

# Time Complexity

| Case         | Complexity |
| ------------ | ---------- |
| Best Case    | O(1)       |
| Average Case | O(log n)   |
| Worst Case   | O(log n)   |

---

# Advantages

* Efficient for large datasets
* Good for infinite lists

---

# Disadvantages

* Requires sorted array

---

# Applications

* Infinite stream searching
* Large databases

---

# 6. Ternary Search

# Introduction

Ternary Search divides array into:

# Three parts

It works on:

* Sorted arrays
* Monotonic functions

---

# Working Principle

1. Divide array into three parts
2. Compare target with two midpoints
3. Continue search in one part

---

# Formula

mid1 = low + \frac{high-low}{3}

mid2 = high - \frac{high-low}{3}

---

# Example

## Array

```text id="s18"
10 20 30 40 50 60 70 80
```

---

# Time Complexity

| Case         | Complexity |
| ------------ | ---------- |
| Best Case    | O(1)       |
| Average Case | O(log₃ n)  |
| Worst Case   | O(log₃ n)  |

---

# Advantages

* Useful in optimization problems

---

# Disadvantages

* More comparisons than binary search
* Complex implementation

---

# Applications

* Mathematical optimization
* Finding maxima/minima

---

# Comparison of Searching Algorithms

| Algorithm | Sorted Required | Best Case | Worst Case |
|---|---|---|
| Linear Search | No | O(1) | O(n) |
| Binary Search | Yes | O(1) | O(log n) |
| Jump Search | Yes | O(1) | O(√n) |
| Interpolation Search | Yes | O(1) | O(n) |
| Exponential Search | Yes | O(1) | O(log n) |
| Ternary Search | Yes | O(1) | O(log₃ n) |

---

# Choosing the Right Searching Algorithm

| Situation                  | Best Algorithm       |
| -------------------------- | -------------------- |
| Small Unsorted Data        | Linear Search        |
| Large Sorted Data          | Binary Search        |
| Uniformly Distributed Data | Interpolation Search |
| Infinite Arrays            | Exponential Search   |
| Optimization Problems      | Ternary Search       |

